history.content:
From a Google search, I'm finding this as the class webpage from last fall, which says that the two classes are taught together, but that undergrads should take only the undergrad version of the class, so presumably this is similar to the difference between 189/289.

Generally, you need instructor approval to sign up for a graduate class, and so if the class policy for next year is the same as that of last year, then you would not be able to get into the class.

Steven is correct that these 3 classes are room-shared. For room-shared/mezzanine courses, undergrads should enroll in the undergrad section e.g. EECS 149 and not EE C249A. There is normally something that distinguishes the grad class from the undergrad in the form of a project or something similar.

I've adjusted the enrollment so there are now a few more seats in EECS 149.

I noticed that these 3 classes are essentially different names for the same class but EECS149 is full while the other twos are barely enrolled. Is there any difference at all if I enroll in any one of these, in terms of grading, requirements, etc? (I'm a rising senior major in CS). Thx~

edit: will I not be able to get into EE C249A or CS C249A because they are "graduate level courses"? I can't really test it right now because I can't add anymore classes for this phase.
